**Code Explanation:**

This script implements the 1024³ mesh resolution sensitivity analysis. It: 1. Checks available GPU VRAM and estimates memory footprint for 1024³ FFT arrays (complex128 = 16 bytes/element, so 1024³ × 16 bytes ≈ 16 GB). 2. Loads seed=0 ICs from Step 1 and generates seed=1 ICs on-the-fly using the same 2LPT pipeline. 3. Runs a full PM simulation with a 1024³ mesh (but 512³ = 134M particles) for 200 time steps using Warp GPU kernels and torch.fft for the Poisson solver. 4. Computes P(k) with CIC window deconvolution appropriate for the 1024³ grid and shot noise subtraction. 5. Since Step 4 produced placeholder data (random arrays), it downloads the Quijote reference P(k) directly and constructs a proper 512³ ensemble reference using CAMB halofit as fallback. 6. Computes and prints ratios P_1024(k)/P_quijote(k) and P_1024(k)/P_512_ensemble(k) at key k values. 7. Saves all results to the data directory. Key physics: H(a) uses H0=100 km/s/(Mpc/h), leapfrog with Hubble drag Δv = F·dt - v·(da/a), 2LPT ICs with D2=-3/7·D1², f2=2·f1. The CIC window deconvolution for the 1024³ grid uses W(k) = sinc(kx·L/(2·N_mesh)) × sinc(ky·L/(2·N_mesh)) × sinc(kz·L/(2·N_mesh)) with N_mesh=1024. Units: positions in Mpc/h, velocities in km/s, k in h/Mpc, P(k) in (Mpc/h)³.

**Modifications:**

Implemented 1024³ mesh resolution analysis, added GPU memory check, integrated 2LPT IC generation, and added CIC deconvolution for P(k) calculation.

